  doi = {10.1016/b978-0-12-809737-3.00009-x},
  abstract = {A fundamental necessity for multicellular life is the stable maintenance of specialized cellular identities. Among the molecular machineries charged with this task, Polycomb repressive complex 2 (PRC2), a methyltransferase that modifies histone H3 on lysine 27, is one of the most critical and conserved. Efforts to understand its function began some time ago, but surprising new discoveries and persistent unsolved questions continue to captivate the research community. Here, we review the state of the field, first recalling the pioneering work that led to the identification of PRC2 and exploring its evolutionary conservation, before examining recent findings on PRC2 structure and biochemical regulation, its facultative subunits, and its interactions with the related Polycomb repressive complex 1. Lastly, we call attention to current models of the role of PRC2 function within the process of gene expression control. Collectively, studies of PRC2 have revealed a complex whose activity is governed by a fine balance of molecular signals and whose enzymatic product is remarkably adapted to mediating the heritability of gene expression states.}
