  abstract = {Abstract   Polycomb group proteins are chromatin-associated transcriptional repressors with essential roles in organism development and differentiation. They exist as part of two main multisubunit complexes, Polycomb repressive complex 1 and 2 (PRC1 and PRC2). PRC1 complexes are defined by a heterodimeric RING-PCGF core capable of monoubiquitinating H2A. Depending on the cofactors that associate with the RING-PCGF core, PRC1 complexes can be further divided into canonical or noncanonical PRC1 (cPRC1 and ncPRC1). The cPRC1 complex is targeted to chromatin through the ability of its CBX subunit to read PRC2-mediated H3K27me3, and it promotes chromatin condensation via heterooligomerisation of its PHC subunits. The various different ncPRC1 complexes are targeted to chromatin independently of H3K27me3 by specific subunits. Recent studies suggest that the majority of PRC1-dependent H2Aub catalytic activity is mediated by the ncPRC1 complexes and that this may partially contribute to the recruitment or activity PRC2. Here we will discuss the data both supporting and conflicting with this hypothesis and examine the emerging evidence for diverse roles of different ncPRC1 complexes in transcriptional regulation, and whether some can contribute to gene activation. Finally, we will also discuss the essential roles of subunits of the cPRC1 and ncPRC1 complexes in the biology of multicellular organisms.}
