  abstract = {Abstract   Polycomb group (PcG) proteins are key players of epigenetic processes, such as Hox gene regulation, X chromosome inactivation, genomic imprinting, stem-cell pluripotency, cell fate determination, reprogramming, and cancer development. PcG proteins repress numerous genes and exert their action through chromatin binding, deposition of specific histone marks, chromatin compaction, and three-dimensional (3D) organization of their target genes. Recent advances in chromosome conformation capture (3C) technologies together with microscopy studies have considerably improved our knowledge of their role in the 3D folding of the genome. In this chapter, we will focus on the molecular mechanisms by which PcG factors exert their action in the kilobase-to-megabase scale of the chromatin fiber, and how this specific nuclear organization can influence gene regulation. We will also discuss the role of noncoding RNAs in shaping PcG-dependent chromosomal organization, and how understanding the mode of Polycomb action in 3D genomics has become increasingly important for research on cancer and other diseases.}
