  abstract = {How a single cell gives rise to multiple cell lineages is a central question in biology. The processes that govern specification of cell identity occur mostly in the absence of modifications of DNA sequence and are thus termed ``epigenetic.'' Once established, defined cellular states have to be perpetuated from mother to daughter cell. Pioneering studies in prokaryotes and then in eukaryotes led to the identification of regulatory proteins termed transcription factors whose function is to modulate gene expression through direct binding of specific DNA sequences. Subsequent work identified a distinct class of regulatory proteins that act at the level of chromatin through covalent modification of histones, chromatin compaction, or nucleosome remodeling. Two such groups of chromatin modifiers, termed Trithorax and Polycomb, are essential for maintaining active (Trithorax) and repressed (Polycomb) expression states of a number of developmental regulators. Importantly, these functions are conserved in multicellular organisms, from metazoans to plants. In this chapter, we will explore the functions of Polycomb and Trithorax proteins during development. We will first emphasize evidence supporting their specific function in regulating maintenance of cellular identity in diverse organisms. We will then examine the molecular mechanisms through which Polycomb and Trithorax proteins function to fine-tune developmental programs.}
